article.headline: Lady Frogs rally in first half, then run away with it
article.linkText: TCU dispatches DePaul to stay in C-USA contention
article.story:
FORT WORTH, Texas (AP) -- Sandora Irvin came out in the second
half with a new jersey and a fast start as No. 17 TCU eliminated
No. 12 DePaul from the Conference USA regular-season title race
with a 73-53 victory Sunday.

Irvin, who finished the day with 19 points and 11 rebounds,
scored seven of the Lady Frogs' first 12 points of the second half.

She had to switch from her regular No. 50 to No. 20 at halftime
because of blood on her jersey.

"I really thought they wouldn't know who she was but I'm pretty
sure they knew who she was," TCU coach Jeff Mittie said.

Both teams entered the game in a second-place tie in the
conference.

TCU (22-4, 11-2) trailed for most of the first half and by as
many as eight points before a 19-5 run in the final seven minutes
gave them a 39-30 lead at halftime. DePaul (22-4, 10-3) was just
1-for-6 from the field during that stretch.

TCU extended its lead during a 12-4 run in the first three
minutes of the second half

"We got out and ran it," Irvin said. "I tried to get Khara
Smith on the floor and the guards got the ball to me."

Kim Ortega had 12 points for TCU and Natasha Lacy and Tiffany
Evans each added 10 points as four Lady Frogs players scored in
double figures.

"I feel like this team is coming together," Mittie said. "I
feel that we're fighting through adverse moments. I liked our fight
in the first half."

He said the team's defense in the second half was as good as he
has seen all year.

Ashley Luke led DePaul with 15 points, and Khara Smith had 14
points and 16 rebounds.

"Once we started hurrying the ball, we never got it back,"
DePaul coach Doug Bruno said. "I thought we were very stiff and
self-pitying after the half."

TCU will have a chance to claim a share of the Conference USA
regular-season title when it plays first-place Houston on Friday.
DePaul finished the regular season with consecutive losses to
Houston and TCU, and can't finish above a tie for second-place.
